Supplementary Information: Models

Laura Geronimo

0.1 Full Sample: Variable Selection Procedure

0.1.1 M0 Stepwise regression on all variables

Here I add all variables to the regression model and then apply stepwise AIC to see what variables are selected

0.1.2 SVSS test

Running SVSS test to see which variables are included

0.1.3 Correlation Matrices on select vars

Note that in preparation for modeling, we examine all of the variables recommended in the SVSS test, plus variables that were significant in the Chi-Square and Anova tests, and are relevant to the literature based on domain knowledge.

Given the high correlation between MHV and MHI, we drop MHI.

Some notes: -MRP ideology is negatively corrleated with PopDense (urban areas more liberal) -MPR ideology is negatively correlated with MHV: as MHV increase, republican ideology decreases (suggests lower-income is correlated with republicanism) -Tax base and MHV are positively correlated -FWhite and MPR ideology are positively correlated

##Stepwise Regression

0.2 Model 1: All hypotheses

0.2.0.0.1 Correlation Matrices for M1

Based on analysis of the correlation matrix, we retain all variables except the Tax Base (corr > 0.5 with MHV). Next we run a model without Fixed effects and check the VIF scores. We include an interaction term on MHV and fWhite

0.2.0.0.2 M1 - Full model WITHOUT fixed effects & select vars

The results of the VIF suggest that all of these variables are ok to include for M1. Now adding fixed effects, as well as an interaction term on fWhite and MHV. Then we run the stepwise procedure to select the final model.

0.2.0.0.3 M1 - Full model with fixed effects & select vars

###Running stepwise to obtain final model for analysis

The stepwise procedure identifies a model that includes 6 variables, and interaction term, and fixed effects.

Note that the stepwise model drops variables of interest like political ideology.
